    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Not Another Sin Tax</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jon Medwich letter says that Hector Batista of American Cancer Society would rather impose 'sin' tax on fast food than hold parents responsible for children's bad eating habits and obesity</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Instead of holding parents accountable for their children's bad eating habits and obesity, Hector Batista, an American Cancer Society official in the New York City region, would rather add a tax to soft drinks and junk food (Public Lives column, July 24).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Instead of holding parents accountable for their children's bad eating habits and obesity, Hector Batista, an American Cancer Society official in the New York City region, would rather add a tax to soft drinks and junk food (Public Lives column, July 24).</p>
        <p>Any ''sin'' tax on fast food would unfairly affect those who eat responsibly and who are not obese; and like the added taxes on cigarettes, it would be an added cost to those who can least afford it.</p>
        <p>JON MEDWICK  New York, July 24, 2003</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
